  "doc_id": "40559",
  "text": "Peripheral oscillators are present in different tissues and expression of CCGs is thought to be tissue-specific. Although it was first though that 10% of the genome is under circadian control [CITATION_1] , recent studies on mouse tissues indicate that roughly 50% of all genes oscillate in a circadian manner [CITATION_2] , reinforcing the idea of a tissue-specific regulation. Although given the increasing number of tissues and cells under circadian investigation and the improvement towards the techniques used to detect also low expressed RNAs and proteins, the number of reported genes showing an oscillating phenotype may increase.",
